<subSubSection id="CDFFA7C82E22A8EF938819133132E171" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="77B5EB10240CB77755500BCAFCC7A9CC" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">
<taxonomicName id="469DB617CC30E32F21E3D122D2C7F094" LSID="29B057AB-B74B-5E95-B291-DD8EF1196893" authority="(Wiegmann, 1834)" baseAuthorityName="Wiegmann" baseAuthorityYear="1834" class="Reptilia" family="Teiidae" genus="Aspidoscelis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidoscelis deppii" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="deppii">Aspidoscelis deppii (Wiegmann, 1834)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4BFA52E370F4C18B1BE97E5587D93C97" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="B1E5DE4919883A5C3455AA20227A4E4D" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E1B33F944E064AE991D0BC597326FC40" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">The species has a wide distribution from Morelos and Michoacan (Mexico) south to Guatemala, El Salvador, Honduras, Nicaragua and Costa Rica.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="752CB93106807C57967967E69D9D76A1" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" type="samples">
<paragraph id="D8F491F21995DE36B4236E781A97B6AC" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Samples.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2E5D933ADFA422DB8413302FB8EAD485" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">RCMX76 (female*) from La Sepultura, Chiapas, Mexico.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="361A900A25B7A4F99D71742CAB13D725" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" type="dna taxonomy">
<paragraph id="9B8937CB5C199F570B3FCF710B56BAC4" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">DNA taxonomy.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7C6D46D8AAF560BCCADA92C7A2CEBF79" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">
The MT-CYB sequence (294-bp) is 4% divergent from GenBank sequences of 
<taxonomicName id="8FCAE9FEE1A8E0C106A3F664AC3EEE6D" baseAuthorityName="Wiegmann" baseAuthorityYear="1834" class="Reptilia" family="Teiidae" genus="Aspidoscelis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidoscelis deppii" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="deppii">
<emphasis id="D5749E10DD60AF6A0C62D3842A10CF17" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Aspidoscelis deppii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(KF555517-21) from Mexico (Playa Miramar, Tabasco). Despite the wide distribution, there are no studies on the intraspecific genetic variability of this species. It is a pity because this slight divergence in the MT-CYB could match with a different karyotype (see below).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="43C2EB0D5EA0E83C07A01C7ACD1D373A" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" type="chromosomes">
<paragraph id="F2022F56D766ED6CD167031E53EB7F71" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Chromosomes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8507F9F5970B5BFDEE5098B7040AF452" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">
In the genus 
<taxonomicName id="6E7335D539F31902891B8549EDE63EAD" authorityName="Fitzinger" authorityYear="1843" class="Reptilia" family="Teiidae" genus="Aspidoscelis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidoscelis" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="6E99C35BE5482C565572DFFD88F69721" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Aspidoscelis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
chromosomal number ranges from 2n = 44 to 2n = 56, with some species showing triploid numbers, such as 
<taxonomicName id="51A6F7C6EC10DD0985C9A4111DB775C8" baseAuthorityName="Say" baseAuthorityYear="1823" class="Reptilia" family="Teiidae" genus="Aspidoscelis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidoscelis tesselatus" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="tesselatus">
<emphasis id="CB1B4A6ADEAE45A8B91E2C292E6459C7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Aspidoscelis tesselatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Say, 1823), with 69 chromosomes (
<bibRefCitation id="31C3E5CC450CA641F6DC30F9A546F623" author="Walker, JM" journalOrPublisher="Herpetologica" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="233 - 259" refId="B73" refString="Walker, JM, Cordes, JE, Taylor, HL, 1997. Parthenogenetic Cnemidophorus tesselatus complex (Sauria: Teiidae): a neotype for diploid C. tesselatus (Say, 1823), redescription of the taxon, and description of a new triploid species. Herpetologica 53: 233 - 259" title="Parthenogenetic Cnemidophorus tesselatus complex (Sauria: Teiidae): a neotype for diploid C. tesselatus (Say, 1823), redescription of the taxon, and description of a new triploid species." volume="53" year="1997">Walker et al. 1997</bibRefCitation>
). The 2n = 44 is the most common diploid number in this genus (
<bibRefCitation id="214C27379D47EA864D2B2382F7D771B4" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/CompCytogen.v9i4.5371" author="Carvalho, NDM" journalOrPublisher="Comparative Cytogenetics" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="625 - 644" refId="B8" refString="Carvalho, NDM, Arias, FJ, da Silva, FA, Schneider, CH, Gross, MC, 2015. Cytogenetic analyses of five amazon lizard species of the subfamilies Teiinae and Tupinambinae and review of karyotyped diversity the family Teiidae. Comparative Cytogenetics 9 (4): 625 - 644, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/CompCytogen.v9i4.5371" title="Cytogenetic analyses of five amazon lizard species of the subfamilies Teiinae and Tupinambinae and review of karyotyped diversity the family Teiidae." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/CompCytogen.v9i4.5371" volume="9" year="2015">Carvalho et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
). Therefore, a low diploid number could represent an ancestral condition. All-acrocentric karyotypes with 2n = 52 (28M + 24m) (
<bibRefCitation id="A82FC462C3CDF723972DE48AA1614F7A" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2412450" author="Lowe, CH" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="128 - 141" refId="B41" refString="Lowe, CH, Wright, JW, Cole, CJ, Bezy, RL, 1970. Chromosomes and evolution of the species groups of Cnemidophorus (Reptilia: Teiidae). Systematic Zoology 19: 128 - 141, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2412450" title="Chromosomes and evolution of the species groups of Cnemidophorus (Reptilia: Teiidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2412450" volume="19" year="1970">Lowe et al. 1970</bibRefCitation>
) and 2n = 50 (26M + 24m) (
<bibRefCitation id="AFE4BA21A9DC05E67BC8B858537B537B" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/1565287" author="Manriquez-Moran, NL" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Herpetology" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="634 - 637" refId="B43" refString="Manriquez-Moran, NL, Villagran-Santa Cruz, M, Mendez de la Cruz, F-R, 2000. Origin and evolution of the parthenogenetic lizards, Cnemidophorus maslini and C. cozumelae. Journal of Herpetology 34: 634 - 637, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/1565287" title="Origin and evolution of the parthenogenetic lizards, Cnemidophorus maslini and C. cozumelae." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/1565287" volume="34" year="2000">
<normalizedToken id="754E3ADCFEFA52231B4B2E1B2F7D7F5E" originalValue="Manríquez-Morán">Manriquez-Moran</normalizedToken>
et al. 2000
</bibRefCitation>
) were reported in 
<taxonomicName id="D0165D179C4DBBD11A5BF3A89FC0D80E" baseAuthorityName="Wiegmann" baseAuthorityYear="1834" class="Reptilia" family="Teiidae" genus="Aspidoscelis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aspidoscelis deppii" order="Squamata" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="deppii">
<emphasis id="F87C2334FFD1097AB9854006ABE1EB24" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">Aspidoscelis deppii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from an unknown location and from Yucatan, respectively. Therefore, the two karyotypes differ in the number of macrochromosomes. Concurrently with 
<bibRefCitation id="F440D4E123564F7AA8E7A8FEA77BD8BB" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2412450" author="Lowe, CH" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="128 - 141" refId="B41" refString="Lowe, CH, Wright, JW, Cole, CJ, Bezy, RL, 1970. Chromosomes and evolution of the species groups of Cnemidophorus (Reptilia: Teiidae). Systematic Zoology 19: 128 - 141, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2412450" title="Chromosomes and evolution of the species groups of Cnemidophorus (Reptilia: Teiidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2412450" volume="19" year="1970">Lowe et al. (1970)</bibRefCitation>
, we found a 2n = 52 (28M + 24m) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B374DEBD96653671E11E319D9636A0A5" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Karyotypes of A Phyllodactylus sp. 3 (2 n = 38, RCMX 69 male) B Holcosus festivus (2 n = 50, RCMX 224 female) C Holcosus undulatus parvus (2 n = 50, RCMX 77 female) D Aspidoscelis deppii (2 n = 52, RCMX 76 female)." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/489816" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">5D</figureCitation>
) all-acrocentric chromosome complement in our sample from Chiapas. This result is also consistent with phylogenetic relationships, since a diploid complement 2n = 52 (28M + 24m) was found in other two species so far analyzed, 
<taxonomicName id="B2156E4E854A81B6B020CF4709CE8F8E" genus="A." lsidName="A. guttatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" rank="species" species="guttatus">
<emphasis id="9D5967B22A164CAE3CAD9144F627FB9C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">A. guttatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Wiegmann, 1834 and 
<taxonomicName id="257298FC648838B7B9A08235EE86392B" genus="A." lsidName="A. lineattissimus" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" rank="species" species="lineattissimus">
<emphasis id="C2A571A6A3BFFC46820E24D288A4081C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">A. lineattissimus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Cope, 1878), which are closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="7B88A48342ADA0EA17909585F01DF3E7" genus="A." lsidName="A. deppii" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" rank="species" species="deppii">
<emphasis id="F6441E2C9ED482A1DB5A5B97C8615C29" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="613">A. deppii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="75DA8397D9A2C49C767BD5596A4AAB8D" DOI="https://doi.org/10.2307/2412450" author="Lowe, CH" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="128 - 141" refId="B41" refString="Lowe, CH, Wright, JW, Cole, CJ, Bezy, RL, 1970. Chromosomes and evolution of the species groups of Cnemidophorus (Reptilia: Teiidae). Systematic Zoology 19: 128 - 141, DOI: https://doi.org/10.2307/2412450" title="Chromosomes and evolution of the species groups of Cnemidophorus (Reptilia: Teiidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.2307/2412450" volume="19" year="1970">Lowe et al. 1970</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="63C6B32AE16EF695DAE288509B923B61" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/CompCytogen.v9i4.5371" author="Carvalho, NDM" journalOrPublisher="Comparative Cytogenetics" pageId="0" pageNumber="613" pagination="625 - 644" refId="B8" refString="Carvalho, NDM, Arias, FJ, da Silva, FA, Schneider, CH, Gross, MC, 2015. Cytogenetic analyses of five amazon lizard species of the subfamilies Teiinae and Tupinambinae and review of karyotyped diversity the family Teiidae. Comparative Cytogenetics 9 (4): 625 - 644, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/CompCytogen.v9i4.5371" title="Cytogenetic analyses of five amazon lizard species of the subfamilies Teiinae and Tupinambinae and review of karyotyped diversity the family Teiidae." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/CompCytogen.v9i4.5371" volume="9" year="2015">Carvalho et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
